content.text:
Yes, exactly. They're full C# classes so you can add any behavior you want directly on them. For example on `Problem`:

```csharp
public class Problem
{
    // ... all the properties ...

    public bool IsAcceptedBy(User user)
    {
        return Submissions.Any(s => s.User.Id == user.Id 
                                 && s.Status == SubmissionStatus.Accepted);
    }

    public double AcceptanceRate()
    {
        if (Submissions.Count == 0) return 0;
        return (double)Submissions.Count(s => s.Status == SubmissionStatus.Accepted) 
               / Submissions.Count * 100;
    }
}
```

Or on `Submission`:

```csharp
public class Submission
{
    // ... all the properties ...

    public bool Passed() => Status == SubmissionStatus.Accepted;

    public bool ExceededLimits() => Status == SubmissionStatus.TimeLimitExceeded 
                                 || Status == SubmissionStatus.MemoryLimitExceeded;
}
```

The pattern of keeping logic on the model class itself is called a **Rich Domain Model**. The alternative (what a lot of ASP.NET projects end up doing) is an **Anemic Domain Model** — classes that are pure data bags with no methods, and all the logic lives in service classes instead.

Neither is strictly wrong, but the general rule of thumb is:

- Logic that's **intrinsic to the object** (does this submission pass? what's the acceptance rate?) → belongs on the model class
- Logic that **coordinates multiple objects or external systems** (score a submission, send a notification, write to the database) → belongs in a service class

So `problem.AcceptanceRate()` makes sense on the model. But `submissionService.EvaluateAndScore(submission)` — which would run the sandbox, compare outputs, update the leaderboard — that belongs in a service because it touches multiple things.

